<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="548" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="13.[113,1089,794,909]" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,291,835,855]" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">Material examined.</emphasis>
<specimenCount box="[296,412,836,855]" pageId="13" pageNumber="548" type="generic">29 specimens</specimenCount>
(9 JJ 
<specimenCount box="[476,534,830,855]" pageId="13" pageNumber="548" type="female">20 ♀♀</specimenCount>
, with 
<specimenCount box="[588,620,830,855]" pageId="13" pageNumber="548" type="female">1 ♀</specimenCount>
macropterous, 1 J 
<specimenCount box="[788,835,830,855]" pageId="13" pageNumber="548" type="female">2 ♀♀</specimenCount>
submacropterous, others brachypterous) from 
<collectingCountry box="[265,345,863,882]" name="Germany" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">Germany</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[354,489,863,882]" name="Czech Republic" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">Czech Republic</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[529,604,863,882]" name="Slovakia" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">Slovakia</collectingCountry>
– localities listed by 
<bibRefCitation author="ROHACEK J." box="[784,926,863,882]" pageId="13" pageNumber="548" pagination="91 - 95" refId="ref9604" refString="ROHACEK J. 1975 a: Uber das Vorkommen einiger Sphaeroceridenarten (Diptera) in einem Auenwald. Folia Facultatis Scientiarum Naturalium Universitatis Purkynianae Brunensis 15 (1), Biologia 43 (1974): 91 - 95." type="journal article" year="1975">ROHÁČEK (1975a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="ROHACEK J." box="[935,980,863,882]" pageId="13" pageNumber="548" pagination="145 - 160" refId="ref9752" refString="ROHACEK J. 1980: Sphaeroceridae (Diptera) collected by the soil trap method in submountaine areas of North Moravia (Czechoslovakia). Casopis Slezskeho Muzea, Opava (A) 29: 145 - 160." type="journal article" year="1980">1980</bibRefCitation>
, 1983, 1999, 2009a) and ROHÁČEK et al. (2005).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[113,1090,933,1277]" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">
The species was originally described as brachypterous (for typical wing see 
<figureCitation box="[994,1076,933,957]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="10.[151,191,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[154,1126,219,1387]" captionTargetId="figure-11@10.[151,1126,219,1387]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs. 31–34. Spelobia pseudonivalis (Dahl, 1909), wings. 31 – submacropterous male (Czech Republic: Nízký Jeseník Mts.– Slunečná Mt.); 32 – slightly brachypterous female (Czech Republic: Hrubý Jeseník – Kouty nad Desnou); 33 – typical brachypterous female (Czech Republic: Horní Benešov env.); 34 – strongly brachypterous female with dm-cu cross-vein lost (Czech Republic: Moravský kras – Babice). Scale: 0.5 mm. Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332531" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332531/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
). The first longer-winged specimens (
<figureCitation box="[496,573,965,989]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="10.[151,191,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[154,1126,219,1387]" captionTargetId="figure-11@10.[151,1126,219,1387]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs. 31–34. Spelobia pseudonivalis (Dahl, 1909), wings. 31 – submacropterous male (Czech Republic: Nízký Jeseník Mts.– Slunečná Mt.); 32 – slightly brachypterous female (Czech Republic: Hrubý Jeseník – Kouty nad Desnou); 33 – typical brachypterous female (Czech Republic: Horní Benešov env.); 34 – strongly brachypterous female with dm-cu cross-vein lost (Czech Republic: Moravský kras – Babice). Scale: 0.5 mm. Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332531" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332531/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
) were recorded by 
<bibRefCitation author="ROHACEK J." box="[779,952,965,989]" pageId="13" pageNumber="548" pagination="145 - 160" refId="ref9752" refString="ROHACEK J. 1980: Sphaeroceridae (Diptera) collected by the soil trap method in submountaine areas of North Moravia (Czechoslovakia). Casopis Slezskeho Muzea, Opava (A) 29: 145 - 160." type="journal article" year="1980">ROHÁČEK (1980)</bibRefCitation>
and its wing polymorphism was discussed by ROHÁČEK (1983). Unfortunately, the relatively small number of specimens available for study makes it impossible to study the phenomenon in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dahl" baseAuthorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Spelobia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudonivalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">S. pseudonivalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
more thoroughly. It seems to be of a similar 
<typeStatus box="[706,752,1062,1086]" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">type</typeStatus>
to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Villeneuve" baseAuthorityYear="1918" box="[789,1047,1062,1085]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Puncticorpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cribratum">
<emphasis box="[789,1047,1062,1085]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">Puncticorpus cribratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but perhaps without geographical dependence and with a much rarer (sub)macropterous form. Among the brachypterous specimens a mutant female with strongly reduced wing and venation (dm-cu lost) was found (
<figureCitation box="[422,500,1157,1181]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="10.[151,191,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[154,1126,219,1387]" captionTargetId="figure-11@10.[151,1126,219,1387]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs. 31–34. Spelobia pseudonivalis (Dahl, 1909), wings. 31 – submacropterous male (Czech Republic: Nízký Jeseník Mts.– Slunečná Mt.); 32 – slightly brachypterous female (Czech Republic: Hrubý Jeseník – Kouty nad Desnou); 33 – typical brachypterous female (Czech Republic: Horní Benešov env.); 34 – strongly brachypterous female with dm-cu cross-vein lost (Czech Republic: Moravský kras – Babice). Scale: 0.5 mm. Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332531" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332531/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
) and recently a fully winged female was recorded from Poľana Mts. in 
<collectingCountry box="[280,373,1189,1213]" name="Slovakia" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">Slovakia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="ROHACEK J." box="[389,562,1189,1213]" pageId="13" pageNumber="548" pagination="260 - 271" refId="ref10357" refString="ROHACEK J. 2009 a: Sphaeroceridae. Pp. 260 - 271. In: ROHACEK J. &amp; SEVCIK J. (eds.): Diptera of the Polana Protected Landscape Area - Biosphere Reserve (Central Slovakia). SNC SR, Administration of the PLA - BR Polana, Zvolen, 340 pp." type="book chapter" year="2009">ROHÁČEK 2009a</bibRefCitation>
). Except for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Richards" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[701,900,1190,1213]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Spelobia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manicata">
<emphasis box="[701,900,1190,1213]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">Spelobia manicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dahl" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[915,1089,1190,1213]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Spelobia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudonivalis">
<emphasis box="[915,1089,1190,1213]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="548">S. pseudonivalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only microcavernicolous wing polymorphic species in Europe. It lives in burrows of small mammals, particularly in nests of moles (ROHÁČEK 1983).
</paragraph>
